==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|joindre|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term/t|la|iungō||join, yoke}}, from Proto-Indo-European ''*yeug-'' “to join, unite”.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈdʒɔɪn/}}
* {{rhymes|ɔɪn}}
* {{audio|en-us-join.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# To [[combine]] more than one item into one; to put together.
#: {{usex|lang=en|The plumber '''joined''' the two ends of the broken pipe.&nbsp;&nbsp; We '''joined''' our efforts to get an even better result.}}
# To come together; to meet.
#* {{w|William Shakespeare}}
#*: Nature and fortune '''joined''' to make thee great.
#: {{usex|lang=en|Parallel lines never '''join'''.&nbsp;&nbsp; These two rivers '''join''' in about 80 miles.}}
# To come into the [[company]] of.
#* {{quote-book|year=1898|author={{w|Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill}}
|title={{w|The Celebrity}}|chapter=4
|passage=No matter how early I came down, I would find him on the veranda, smoking cigarettes, or otherwise his man would be there with a message to say that his master would shortly '''join''' me if I would kindly wait.}}
#: {{usex|lang=en|I will '''join''' you watching the football game as soon as I have finished my work.}}
# To become a member of.
#: {{usex|lang=en|Many children '''join''' a sports club.&nbsp;&nbsp; Most politicians have '''joined''' a party.}}
# {{context|computing|databases|transitive|lang=en}} To produce an [[intersection]] of [[data]] in two or more [[database]] [[table]]s.
#: {{usex|lang=en|By '''joining''' the Customer table on the Product table, we can show each customer's name alongside the products they have ordered.}}
# To unite in marriage.
#* Wyclif
#*: he that '''joineth''' his virgin in matrimony
#* Bible, Matthew xix. 6
#*: What, therefore, God hath '''joined''' together, let not man put asunder.
# {{cx|obsolete|rare|lang=en}} To [[enjoin]] upon; to [[command]].
#* Tyndale
#*: They '''join''' them penance, as they call it.
# To accept, or engage in, as a contest.
#: ''to '''join''' encounter, battle, or issue''
#: {{rfquotek|Milton}}

